         "id": "SECTION_local_content",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>The Myth of a Flat Earth</h3></p><p class=\"desc\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\"><g fill=\"grey\" transform=\"rotate(-10 50 100) translate(-6 35.5) skewX(40) scale(0.7 0.3)\"> <rect width=\"14vw\" height=\"10vw\" x=\"10\" y=\"10\" fill=\"gray\" /> </g></svg></svg></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<h4>What is a Plane?</h4>To answer this question, we can simplify the definition given by Eric W. Weisstein: a plane is a rigid, two-dimensional surface",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e6658b62-fb15-446c-ab20-44f2b6459b1d",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "The mathematical definition of a plane alone excludes the possibility of a flat Earth. As we’ve discussed, continents and oceans are not rigid surfaces; they are made of matter, which is part of the observable universe and has mass. This mass requires Earth to have a third dimension, making it impossible for Earth to be a perfectly flat surface",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "59c0b962-d032-4b6c-9498-2341e089510b",
                     "text": "Allmon, D. W. et al",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "750e84b5-9330-4f99-92b0-72469a6a64f4",
                     "text": "Allmon, D. W. et al",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "910e016f-246e-44dc-8f76-430fe6e9c01d",
                     "text": "Britannica, T. Editors of Encyclopaedia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "We can further confirm this by observing a lunar eclipse. In these events, the Moon is not partially covered by a flat shadow; instead, a curved shadow is projected onto its surface—something the ancient Greeks had already observed",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7b82ec3f-a292-48b4-8945-58e2d154f499",
                     "text": "Brown, Cynthia S",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "27"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<h4>The Origin of the Flat Earth Myth</h4>The myth of a flat Earth is, in fact, a relatively recent idea that emerged in the 19th century, rooted in false narratives. Among these was the incorrect claim that Christopher Columbus \"proved\" the Earth was round and that Greek knowledge of Earth’s shape had been lost. In reality, Columbus and his contemporaries were primarily concerned with the logistical challenges of a long voyage, such as the availability of supplies, as it was already well-known that Earth’s circumference was around 40,000 kilometers",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d94d235c-a97d-48dd-a18c-6b7d6db9e8ab",
                     "text": "Russel, Jeffrey B.",
                     "page": "pp. 1 -11, 27 - 49",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1991",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f7fe2b60-85fc-4c16-8fe7-120f7b9236a4",
                     "text": "Gould, Stephan J.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1996",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "According to historian Jeffrey Burton Russell, before <htdate0>, Columbus \"discovery\" of a round Earth was mentioned only superficially in some schoolbooks. However, by the <htdate1>, this narrative had become widely accepted in educational texts. The idea that Greek knowledge of Earth’s shape was entirely forgotten is also tied to a false narrative suggesting a supposed conflict between science and religion",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d94d235c-a97d-48dd-a18c-6b7d6db9e8ab",
                     "text": "Russel, Jeffrey B.",
                     "page": "pp. 1 -11, 27 - 49",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1991",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f7fe2b60-85fc-4c16-8fe7-120f7b9236a4",
                     "text": "Gould, Stephan J.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1996",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
